My personal vimfiles, crafted carefully with time.

Plugins used:
  c.vim         (http://www.vim.org/scripts/script.php?script_id=213)
  Command-T     (http://github.com/wincent/Command-T)
  gist-vim      (http://github.com/mattn/gist-vim)
  matchit       (http://www.vim.org/scripts/script.php?script_id=39)
  nerdcommenter (http://github.com/scrooloose/nerdcommenter)
  nerdtree      (http://github.com/scrooloose/nerdtree)
  snipmate.vim  (http://github.com/msanders/snipmate.vim)
  syntastic     (http://github.com/scrooloose/syntastic)
  vim-cucumber  (http://github.com/tpope/vim-cucumber)
  vim-pathogen  (http://github.com/tpope/vim-pathogen)
  vim-rails     (http://github.com/tpope/vim-rails)
  vim-repeat    (http://github.com/tpope/vim-repeat)
  vim-ruby      (http://github.com/vim-ruby/vim-ruby)
  vim-surround  (http://github.com/tpope/vim-surround)

Installation
cd
mv .vim .vim_old
git clone git://github.com/murilasso/vimfiles ~/.vim
cd ~/.vim
git submodule init
git submodule update

Also, put "source ~/.vim/vimrc" (without the quotes) inside the .vimrc in your home directory.

Notes
To make vim-ruby's completions (among other stuff) work, vim must be compiled with ruby support.

To check if you vim has ruby support type `vim --version |grep ruby` in your terminal. If the output contains '+ruby' you're good to go. If not, you must compile vim with ruby support.

Also, to make gist-vim work, you need to set your github token in gitconfig.
